05142nam a22007695i 9781442632066DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2016    onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426320667 a10.3138/97814426320662doi  a(DE-B1597)465775  a(OCoLC)1013957283  a(OCoLC)944178862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHD1511.C22 7aHIS0060102bisacsh04a333.3/17170917341 aBittermann, Rusty, eauthor.10aRural Protest on Prince Edward Island :bFrom British Colonization to the Escheat Movement /cRusty Bittermann. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Eighteenth-Century Roots of Rural Protest -- t2. Land Issues in a Changing Context, 1800-1824 -- t3. The Limitations of Developmental Politics, 1824-1831 -- t4. Escheat Enters the Political Arena, 1831-1833 -- t5. Resistance in the Countryside, 1832-1834 -- t6. Organizing Proprietors, 1831-1834 -- t7. Organizing Escheat, 1834-1836 -- t8. Harvey and the Escheators, 1836-1837 -- t9. Agrarian Institutions and the March to Power, 1837-1838 -- t10. The Limits of Democratic Power, 1838-1842 -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWho has the more legitimate claim to land, settlers who occupy and improve it with their labour, or landlords who claim ownership on the basis of imperial grants? This question of property rights, and their construction, was at the heart of rural protest on Prince Edward Island for a century. Tenants resisted landlord claims by squatting and refusing to pay rent. They fought for their vision of a just rural order through petitions, meetings, rallies, electoral campaigns, and direct action. Landlords responded with their own collective action to protect their interests. In Rural Protest on Prince Edward Island Rusty Bittermann examines this conflict and the dynamic of rural protest on the Island from its establishment as a British colony in the 1760s to the early 1840s.The focus of Bittermann's study is the remarkable mass movement known as the Escheat movement, which emerged in the 1830s in the context of growing popular challenges elsewhere in the Atlantic World. The Escheat movement aimed at resolving the land question in favour of tenants by having the state resume (escheat) the large grants of land that created landlordism on the Island. Although it ultimately gained control of the assembly in the late 1830s, the Escheat movement did not produce the land policies that tenants and their allies advocated. The movement did, however, synthesize years of rural protest and produce a persistent legacy of language and ideas concerning land, justice, and the rights of small producers that helped to make landlordism on the Island unsustainable in the long term. Rural Protest on Prince Edward Island is a comprehensive and fascinating examination of an important, but often overlooked, period in the history of Canada's smallest province.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aFarm tenancyzPrince Edward IslandxHistoryy19th century. 0aLand reformzPrince Edward IslandxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442632066423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442632066.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBoo